Beijing's natural ecology continues to improve, attracting more than 500 species of wild animals and cities to "settle "-Chinanews.com
2020-07-2605: 03: 17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sishuo
The capital's natural ecology continues to improve to attract wildlife cities to "settle"
There are more than 500 species of wild animals in Beijing
News from our newspaper (Reporter Wang Bin) The reporter from the Beijing Youth Daily learned from the Municipal Landscaping Bureau that with the continuous improvement of the capital's natural ecological environment in recent years, the types and numbers of wild animals have also continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial spine wild animals that inhabit Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including national first-class protected animals such as brown horse chicken and black stork, as well as national second-level protected animals such as gazelle, big swan, gray crane, mandarin duck.
Whether it is planted into the urban forests in the second ring, or the small wetlands embedded in the buildings, it not only brings the wild interest of nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wild animals to "settle" in the city.
In midsummer, the Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is full of vitality.
A raccoon was playing leisurely by the mountain stream, and two dog badgers were fighting each other.
Looking back, a wild boar can't help but scratch his body and is rubbing hard against the bark. Hu Qiaoli, director of the Songshan National Nature Reserve Administration, introduced that as of the end of 2019, in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares, there are 178 species of wild animals, including the national first-class protected animal golden eagle and the national second-class protected animal spoon chicken and antelope. Nearly one-third of the city's wild animal species can be found here.
"In Songshan, wild animals are the real 'owners', and our staff can only be regarded as' bodyguards' at best."
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to understand the situation of wild animals and plants in the reserve on the ground, there are more than 30 professional rangers every day, patrolling along 16 carefully formulated protection routes, and there will be a "big circle" every month, spending a whole day almost traveling through the entire reserve.
"During the inspection, it is not only necessary to check and record biodiversity, but also to inspect and install artificial bird nests, rescue injured wild animals, install field infrared cameras, etc."
Songshan National Nature Reserve has now installed more than 200 infrared cameras to record the living conditions of wild animals in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli introduced that with the continuous enrichment of biodiversity in the reserve in recent years, more and more wild animals have appeared in the lens, leopard cats, raccoons and pig badgers have become "resident guests", and the "appearance rate" of the national second-level protected animal antelope is also getting higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, Director of the Wildlife and Wetland Protection Division of the Beijing Municipal Bureau of Landscaping, introduced that the number of terrestrial spine wild animals in Beijing has increased from 461 species in 1994 to more than 500 now. The types and numbers of wild animals in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years.
The presence of wild animals in cities has become more common, which is closely related to the continuous upgrading of greening in the capital city in recent years.
In particular, the new round of one million mu afforestation and greening construction, which began in 2018, proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, improve the ecological function of woodland green space, and highlight the concept of "near nature."
The planning strives to achieve interconnection and interaction with the surrounding green spaces to facilitate wild animals to "visit relatives and friends", and the trees planted are also honey and food plants that animals love.
Black land "planted" out of agricultural modernization-Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Harbin, July 26, title: Black land "planted" out of agricultural modernization
In the midsummer, two spraying planes passed by the 10,000 mu high-yield demonstration field in the second operation station of the fifth management area of Friendship Farm, forming two white lines, and the big words "the first field in the world" planted with black rice seedlings in the green field stand out.
Kong Lingqiang, director of this operation station, said that this kind of aircraft can spray more than 6,000 acres of cultivated land a day, and the efficiency is about 8 times that of drones and hundreds of times that of humans.
This farm is located in Youyi County, Heilongjiang Province, my country's first grain-producing province. From the sound of rice cutting in the past to the sound of "rumbling" motors today, traditional Chinese farming and farms have been transformed on this black soil belt.
In addition to airplanes, satellites are also used in the modern agricultural production of Friendship Farm.
Kong Lingqiang introduced that on the one hand, they use satellite remote sensing technology to achieve precise fertilization, reduce agricultural input, and reduce pollution; on the other hand, satellite navigation technology can improve the level of standardized agricultural machinery field operations.
During this year's rice production process, the farm expanded the operating area of satellite navigation unmanned rice transplanting technology from 3,000 mu last year to 30,000 mu.
This technology makes the planting of seedlings more uniform, maximizes the use of sunlight and arable land resources, and saves 16 yuan in labor costs per mu.
The farm tried new technologies such as informatization and intelligence in agricultural production, forming the largest agricultural machinery group in my country from the ground to the sky.
According to statistics, the total number of farm machinery held at present is 49,000 units (pieces), and the comprehensive mechanization rate in the field has reached 99.8%.
Agricultural machinery operations achieve 100% GPS satellite navigation, 100% precision seeding in dry fields, and 100% operation in dry fields.
"Green agriculture, smart agriculture, and digital agriculture are the direction of agricultural modernization."
Liu Hualien, director of Friendship Farm, said.
The key to agricultural modernization lies in scientific and technological progress.
Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation, represented by farms, has played a demonstration and leading role in modern large-scale agriculture "aircraft carrier" in recent years, and has initially established a modern agricultural industry system led by large-scale planting, standardized production, and industrial management.
On the outskirts of Youyi County, there is an Agricultural Machinery Expo Park covering an area of 350,000 square meters.
Here is a concentrated exhibition of more than 140 agricultural machinery and equipment introduced and used by Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation over the years.
These agricultural machinery and farms bear witness to the development of China's agricultural modernization.
Xie Xiaojia for everyone-the transfer of the masses in Jiangkouhe, Hefei, Anhui Province-Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Hefei, July 26, title: Shi Xiaojia for everyone-Jiang Kouhe Lianhe, Hefei, Anhui
Xinhua News Agency reporters Chen Shangying, Wang Liwu, Liu Xia Village
At 4 o'clock in the afternoon on July 25, Fu Kunbao, dressed in muddy rubber shoes, went from the former house to the back room, and his wife Zhou Yan came back and forth busy packing things.
"When I received a call from the village cadre to transfer, I was still weeding in the field."
Fu Kunbao said that he has transferred more than 60 acres of land and planted rice, and is now growing well. "I took medicine yesterday, and I haven't packed my tools yet."
Fu Kunbao pointed to the pesticide sprayer placed in the corner. "No one wants his home to be flooded, let's leave a small home for everyone."
In order to cope with the continued high water level pressure and possible heavy rainfall in Chaohu Lake, Hefei City, Anhui Province, is preparing to open the Jiangkouhe Lianhe flood distribution and water storage station where Fu Kunbao's family is located on the 26th.
Jiangkouhe Lianwei is located in Feixi County, next to the Chaohu dike.
There are thousands of villagers involved in Yan Dian Township and Sanhe Town in the polder who need to be transferred.
As of 16: 00 on the 25th, the water level of Chaohu Lake, China's fifth largest freshwater lake, remained at a high level of 13.2 meters, 0.7 meters above the guaranteed water level.
Fu Kunbao's kitchen is clean and tidy. There is a pot of pumpkin head vegetables on the table, and there are eggs and some brine in the refrigerator.
"I didn't expect to move. The water in Jiangkouhe looks good at the moment."
Zhou Yan said that the home is a bungalow, and some large objects have not been decided where to put them for the time being.
"Pack up valuable items first, and large items such as refrigerators and televisions can be placed in the homes of high-lying neighbors or relatives for the time being."
Village cadre Wang Liwen gave Fu Kunbao an idea.
Wang Lixiang is responsible for the transfer and resettlement of 13 villagers, and notifies each household to confirm everyone's resettlement plan.
The nearest resettlement site to Fu Kunbao's family is Su Primary School in Yan Dian Township, about 2 kilometers away.
In addition to the large items, Fu Kunbao and his wife have a headache with more than 1,000 jin of grain and some newly bought furniture in the family.
"The food is going to be dragged to a relative's house, and the furniture can't be moved."
As soon as the couple discussed, they put a stool under the newly bought bed and raised the bed by about half a meter.
At 6 o'clock in the afternoon, Fu Kunbao began to use a tricycle to transport things to relatives' homes. Zhou Yan continued to clean up at home.
At 11 o'clock in the evening, the couple looked back and forth at home, pulled on the switch, and were ready to go to the resettlement site.
"I hope the water will retire early."
Fu Kunbao said.
At 9: 30 am on July 26, the reporter saw at the scene of Jiangkouhe Lianwei that the local area has made preparations for flood distribution.
