Church fire in Nantes, France: Diocese volunteers admit to arson and silence-Chinanews.com
China News Service, July 26. According to foreign media reports, on July 18, the treasures of religious and historical buildings in Nantes, France, and the famous Cathedral of St. Peter and St. Paul, were severely damaged in a fire, and the large pipe organ was completely destroyed.
On the 26th local time, the Nantes prosecutor announced that a diocese volunteer who was responsible for defense work in the cathedral had been charged with "arson and destruction."
He has admitted that he set the fire in the church.
According to the report, local prosecutor Senas said that the 39-year-old parish volunteer from Rwanda admitted that he had set fire to three places in the cathedral at night.
The person's lawyer said that the arsonists now regret doing such a thing.
This person entered France through the route of asylum a few years ago, was sheltered in the parish where the fire happened, and was taken in in the church.
The prosecutor pointed out that recently, he tried to renew his visa and is talking to the police station about this.
But the church said it still cannot believe that this believer, who is usually very kind and smiling, but doesn't talk much, will destroy the church he loves so much.
On the day of the fire on July 18, the volunteer had already been questioned and investigated by the police because of illogical problems in the narrative, but he was later released.
The picture shows firefighters rescuing at the scene.
On the evening of the 25th, as professional engineers from the laboratory of the Paris Central Police Department obtained new evidence, this person was summoned again.
This time, the man admitted his arson.
According to reports, if the charge of deliberate arson and destruction is convicted, the suspect may face 10 years in prison and a fine of 150,000 euros.
According to reports, the fire caused serious damage to the Cathedral of St. Pierre and St. Paul. The pipe organ in the church was completely burned, and the stained glass window behind the pipe organ was also severely damaged.
Brunet, the chief architect of the French historic preservation building, believes that it is conservatively estimated that the restoration of the Nantes Cathedral will take at least three years.
