The engine may be extinguished. FAA urgently ordered the investigation of 2,000 Boeing airliners-Xinhuanet
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring emergency inspections of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737 Classic airliners registered in the United States. The reason is that the corrosion of the air check valve of the above-mentioned airliner may cause the engine to park in the air.
The FAA said that it has so far received 4 reports of 737NG and 737Classic passenger aircraft engine parking in the air, so it has made an emergency inspection request. The inspection object is the passenger plane that has been parked for 7 days or more continuously and the passenger plane that has flown less than 11 times so far after being relaunched.
The FAA warned that if the level 5 check valves of all two engines of the airliner are corroded, they may become stuck in the open position, causing the airliner to completely lose power and unable to restart the engine.
This aviation regulatory agency ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, the airline operator must replace this key component before the passenger plane is put into service again.
Boeing responded later that day that the outbreak of the new crown epidemic has reduced travel demand, and many passenger planes have been sealed or used less, and "check valves are more likely to be corroded."
Boeing also said that it has advised air operators to inspect the passenger aircraft involved in the directive, and if problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in repairing and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that airliners owned by major U.S. air operators usually fly many times in a day, but after the outbreak of the new crown epidemic, a large number of airliners were grounded; as passenger travel demand has slowly increased recently, some airliners have returned to operation.
The FAA did not release the details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that one of its airliners was en route from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas, on July 15, when an engine suddenly turned off, and the airliner finally made an emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said that it had replaced the engine of the airliner and had inspected the engines of six airliners in accordance with FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines, and Southwest Airlines said separately on the 24th that their airliners did not have engine outages associated with air check valves.
Four airliners under American Airlines will be inspected, and 28 passenger aircraft under United Airlines will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 passenger aircraft, but did not say whether there had been engine outages.
Many media reported that the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive is another impact on Boeing.
Indonesian Lion Airlines and Ethiopian Airlines each crashed a Boeing 737MAX airliner in October 2018 and March 2019 respectively, killing a total of 346 people.
This series of airliners was subsequently grounded worldwide. Production ceased in January this year, and production resumed in May.
FAA Director Steve Dickson admitted in June that the FAA "made a mistake" in its supervision of Boeing with regard to the 737MAX airliner.
