Lewis Family: John Lewis is a soldier who "fights for the weakest."
U.S. Congressman and civil rights fighter John Lewis (John Lewis) was remembered as a fighter "fighting for the weakest" at a memorial service held for him on Saturday (July 25).
Lewis' public memorial service has been held in Alabama since Saturday.
There were two memorial services on the first day.
At a public memorial service at Troy University in Alabama on Saturday, Lewis' five brothers and sisters and a nephew talked about him as a loving, unafraid, family-oriented man.
Lewis' youngest brother, Henry "Grant" Lewis, said at the meeting: "He devoted his life to helping others."
Samuel Lewis said that his mother had warned John "not to cause trouble, not to cause trouble."
He added that John did not heed his mother's warning. He said: "We all know that John always gets into trouble and always gets into trouble, but that's because he insists on the right thing, and that's good trouble."
Lewis' brothers and sisters reminded the people at the memorial service that John's most famous argument is to create "good trouble", that is, as long as it is for the sake of justice, he will not shy away from provoking trouble.
John once applied to Troy University in Troy, Alabama, where he was born, but Troy University, which was an all-white school at the time, rejected his application for admission.
John Lewis, who preached the gospel to chickens on his farm as a child, eventually received a degree in religion and philosophy from Fisk University.
Many years later, Troy University awarded Lewis an honorary doctorate.
Congressman Doug Jones from Alabama said that the current protesters are "protesting peacefully and non-violently", just like Lewis did in the civil rights movement.
Jones said: "Even if President Trump knocked over a boat and described all the protesters as thugs, he was wrong.
The protesters are patriots, and they want the United States to move towards a more equal country. "
A six-day series of events to commemorate Lewis will culminate this week at a funeral in Georgia.
Lewis' coffin was parked at a public memorial service at Troy University on Saturday, and people came to pay tribute to the pioneer of the civil rights movement.
Later on Saturday, a private ceremony paid tribute to him in a small church in Selma, Alabama, followed by a public memorial service.
On Sunday, Lewis' body will pass through the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma.
In 1965, he and the demonstrators who demanded the right to vote for blacks were severely beaten by the Alabama police in front of this bridge, and the police also released tear gas on the demonstrators.
Lewis was almost killed at the time.
This day will later be called "Bloody Sunday."
Lewis' body will be transported to Montgomery, the capital of Alabama.
Mayor Steven Reed encouraged people to line up on the sidewalk to complete this final journey with Lewis.
At the same time, officials require the public to wear masks and maintain social distance when participating in activities.
Alabama Governor Kay Ivey ordered that the flag be lowered at half mast on Saturday and Sunday to commemorate Lewis.
During the nearly week-long commemoration, Lewis's body will be placed in the Alabama State Capitol in Montgomery, the Georgia State Capitol in Atlanta, and the U.S. Capitol in Washington for people to express their condolences.
House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell announced last week that people can come to the U.S. Capitol on Monday and Tuesday to pay tribute to Lewis.
Due to the coronavirus epidemic, a public event to mourn Lewis will be held outdoors.
