Cocoa Xili Tibetan antelope enters the return season-Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) The reporter learned from the Wudaoliang Protection Station of the Coxili Management Office of Jiangyuan Park, Director of Sanjiangyuan National Park, that monitoring showed that the Tibetan antelopes that had previously migrated to the Zhuonai Lake area in the hinterland of Coxili to give birth are gradually ending their birth and beginning to return to their original habitat with their cubs.
Surveillance footage near the Wudaoliang Protection Station shows that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelopes led 3 Tibetan antelope cubs through 3002 kilometers of the Qinghai-Tibet Highway and the five-way Liangbei Bridge of the Qinghai-Tibet Railway. The Tibetan antelope has begun to migrate back.
Experts analyze that in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope cubs in the returning herd accounted for one-quarter to one-fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope flocks.
Lien Xinming, deputy researcher at the Northwest Plateau Biology Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: "At the beginning of the return migration, the Tibetan antelope faces a higher risk of predation, so the number of cubs in the flock will be relatively small, and there may even be no cubs."
According to statistics from the Cocoa Xili Management Office of Jiangyuan Park, Director of Sanjiangyuan National Park Management, the number of Tibetan antelopes returning has been increasing year by year. The number of Tibetan antelopes returning in 2019 was 4,860, an increase of 338 over 2018.
Liang Xinming said: "It is expected that the return migration of Tibetan antelopes this year will end in early September, and the number of returning Tibetan antelopes is still expected to continue to increase."
The Tibetan antelope is a national first-class protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelopes from Sanjiangyuan in Qinghai, Qiangtang in Tibet, and Aljinshan in Xinjiang all travel to Zhuonai Lake in the hinterland of Cocosiri to give birth to lambs.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert on the protection of Tibetan antelopes in my country and a researcher at the Shaanxi Institute of Zoology (Northwest Endangered Animals Research Institute), said: "The return of Tibetan antelopes is the process of female Tibetan antelopes returning to their habitat after giving birth. At first, the returning groups that left the breeding ground were relatively large, but then the Tibetan antelopes will return to their respective habitats according to different geographical populations and along different paths."
In order to ensure the safe relocation of Tibetan antelope sheep, the reporter learned that the Cocoa Xili Management Office of Jiangyuan Park, Director of Sanjiangyuan National Park Management, has arranged staff to continuously carry out video monitoring and jurisdictional patrols in the main relocation area.
If a Tibetan antelope flock is found trying to cross the highway, the mountain patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control at the first time to allow the flock to pass safely through the wildlife passage to ensure that it is as little human interference as possible on the way back.
