Hao Yusheng, Chief Representative of Nasdaq China: Now is the best time node for Chinese companies to go to the United States for IPOs-Economic Watch-Professional Financial News Website
Economic Observer Network reporter Zhang Bin Because of the Ruixing Coffee counterfeiting incident, the US market has imposed stricter supervision on Chinese concept stocks, coupled with the long-term pressure on valuations, and Chinese concept stocks listed in the United States are under pressure. Netease, JD.com and other Chinese concept stocks have recently begun their journey back to Hong Kong for listing.
Recently, shell, ideal car and other companies have been eager to go public in the United States.
Under the epidemic and the Chinese concept stock crisis, is now the best time for Chinese companies to go public in the United States?
"As far as the recent IPO cases and the next companies to be listed in the United States are concerned, the IPO to the United States has not been affected in essence, but the market is very good now, and even this point in time is the best time node for Chinese companies to go to the United States for IPOs in the past 10 years."
Hao Yusheng, chief representative of the China region of the Nasdaq Stock Exchange, said at the "2020 Listed Company Leaders Summit China Equity Branch" hosted by Snowball.
In April this year, the US Securities Regulatory Commission (SEC) and the Public Company Accounting Regulatory Board (PCAOB) issued the "Statement on the Important Role of Audit Quality and Supervision in Obtaining Audit and Other International Information-A Discussion on the Current Challenges of Information Acquisition for US Listed Companies with a large number of operations in China."
The statement stated that although international cooperation and coordination have increased significantly in recent years, the U.S. regulatory authorities still have problems with access to information, and the SEC and PCAOB still face legal and practical challenges; corresponding to this document, the PCAOB website provides a detailed list of listed companies that have encountered audit obstacles and their audit institutions, and a large number of Chinese concept stock companies are listed.
In addition, in May this year, the U.S. Senate passed the "Foreign Companies Accountability Act", which introduced additional information disclosure requirements for foreign companies to list in the United States.
In Hao Yusheng's view, the Chinese stock crisis has not affected the appetite of investors.
"When this news first came out, it caused everyone's panic, and everyone was asking if they could go public in the United States in the future, but later we found that these problems are not a problem on the investor's side. Investors may ask these questions during the recent IPO roadshow in the United States, and even become standardized questions, but this has not been regarded by investors as an important factor in investing in a Chinese company.
It is suggested that everyone treat the current situation with a normal heart as much as possible.
Of course, this time may look like the worst situation in the past two years, but as far as investors' appetite is concerned, it has not been affected in any way.
So from now until the end of this year or before the US election, the upsurge of IPOs to the United States will continue. "
On May 9 this year, Jinshan Yun officially listed on Nasdaq in the United States, becoming the first Chinese company to go to the United States for an IPO after the epidemic.
"The listing of Jinshan Yun gives a lot of confidence to the Chinese companies that are preparing for IPOs later."
Hao Yusheng said.
The report on Chinese stocks in the first half of 2020 released by Snowball shows that in the first half of this year, a total of 20 Chinese companies went to the US for IPOs, an increase of 17.6% over the same period last year; in terms of total initial fund-raising, 20 companies raised a total of 2.725 billion, up more than 52.4% from the same period last year. In terms of industry distribution, the number of IPOs in the healthcare industry in the first half of this year was outstanding, an increase of 100% over the same period last year.
According to Hao Yusheng, the quality of Chinese companies that went to the United States for IPOs in the first half of this year is relatively high, and high-quality companies with strong fundamentals and growth will be more favored by investors.
In the short, medium and long term, Hao Yusheng continues to be optimistic about Ming China's IPO in the United States.
"In the short term, the wave of IPOs to the United States continues; in the medium term, Chinese companies have more choices, A shares, Hong Kong stocks, and US stocks. Everyone will take the US general election and Sino-US relations as factors for market selection and time selection; in the long run, everything will return to normal, and market fluctuations are cycles, both political and economic, and will eventually return to the normal stage, and the stock market has always been fluctuating."
Hao Yusheng also said, "There are more uncertain factors this year, but for high-quality companies, no matter whether the market is good or bad, as long as they are solid and have growth that investors can see, other factors are relatively minor. Investors need to invest in outstanding Chinese companies."
