China News Service, Xiamen, July 26 (Yang Fushan Zhang Shushan Xu Jingyi) China's famous vascular surgery center-Shanghai Changhai Hospital Vascular Surgery, Naval Military Medical University, signed a contract with the Department of Vascular Surgery of Zhongshan Hospital Affiliated to Xiamen University on the 25th to establish a collaboration center to promote exchanges and cooperation between the two sides in the field of vascular surgery, especially in the field of acute and severe aortic diseases.
Zhongshan Hospital Affiliated to Xiamen University said that after the vascular surgery of the two hospitals formally formed a collaborative unit, they will carry out remote consultations, make real-time online consultations with Changhai Hospital to formulate treatment plans, select talents for further training, and jointly carry out surgical technology exchanges, teaching and room searches every week; for complex cases, Changhai experts can be invited to the hospital to perform operations according to the needs of the patients, so that patients in southwestern Fujian can enjoy the top domestic medical resources without leaving the province.
The two hospitals will also work together to carry out surgical innovation and scientific research, aortic disease popularization and early screening, etc.
The aortic special seminar hosted by Beijing Health Promotion Association and hosted by Zhongshan Hospital Affiliated to Xiamen University was held in Xiamen on the same day.
The above-mentioned two well-known hospitals in Shanghai and Xiamen held a signing ceremony for the Vascular Surgery Collaboration Center at the same time at the meeting, announcing the formation of a collaborative unit to jointly improve the treatment level of vascular surgery-related diseases in southwestern Fujian.
Shanghai Changhai Hospital Vascular Surgery is the only vascular surgery institute in the army and the only vascular system disease clinical medicine center in Shanghai. It is also the first national key discipline of vascular surgery. It led the establishment of the Chinese Physicians Association Endovascular Angiology Professional Committee, which is a well-established top team in the industry.
Professor Huang Xiaojin, Director of Vascular Surgery, Zhongshan Hospital Affiliated to Xiamen University, was interviewed by the media.
The Vascular Surgery Department of Zhongshan Hospital Affiliated to Xiamen University is the first vascular surgery set up by an independent discipline in Fujian Province. It has long been committed to the diagnosis and treatment of aortic and peripheral vascular diseases. In 2018, it was approved to build a provincial key clinical specialty.
In the treatment of aortic diseases, in addition to the treatment of dissecting aneurysms and aortic aneurysms, there is extensive experience in emergency ruptured aortic aneurysms.
"The vascular surgery of Zhongshan Hospital Affiliated to Xiamen University is very outstanding in this region in terms of the history of development, the breadth, difficulty, and complexity of the operation, so this time we set up a collaboration center. In addition to the aorta, it can also carry out in-depth cooperation in medicine, teaching, and scientific research in the diagnosis and treatment of diseases such as lower extremity arteries and carotid arteries."
Professor Feng Rui, deputy director of vascular surgery at Shanghai Changhai Hospital, said.
Zhongshan Hospital Affiliated to Xiamen University and Shanghai Changhai Hospital signed a contract to establish a "Li Zhaoshen Famous Medical Studio" in the Department of Gastroenterology in 2018.
Professor Huang Xiaojin, director of vascular surgery of the hospital, said in an interview with a reporter from Chinanews.com that the vascular surgery of the hospital has also been in communication with Changhai Hospital for a long time. This time, the two hospitals formally formed a collaborative unit, bringing cooperation and exchanges between the two sides to a new level.
He said that the hospital will regularly invite Shanghai experts to Xiamen to carry out surgical technology exchanges, teaching room searches, difficult case discussions, etc., and further carry out remote consultations. Currently, it plans to conduct remote consultations once a week; in addition, the department will also send personnel for further training and exchanges to strengthen the training and development of disciplinary talent teams.
The reporter learned at the meeting that vascular disease is the largest cause of death in China, and the aorta, as the main artery of various organs of the human body, flows from the heart to the whole body and plays an important role.
The occurrence of aortic diseases is often accompanied by high risk, high mortality, and high difficulty in treatment. The thickest section of the aorta is up to 4 cm in diameter. Once a hemangioma is formed, rupture occurs, or the vascular intima ruptures to produce dissection, it will cause massive bleeding, which is very dangerous.
In recent years, as people's lifestyles have changed and the pace of life has accelerated, China has become the world's largest country with hypertension, and aortic diseases have also increased. Today, with the development of surgical techniques and industrial materials, the treatment of aortic diseases continues to develop in the direction of minimally invasive, rapid and efficient.
Doctors can properly "divert" blood flow by piercing the thigh and placing a stent in the aorta, so as to avoid the impact on the aneurysm or ruptured dissection, and achieve a good therapeutic effect. Some operations even require local anesthesia.
This academic seminar invited more than a dozen domestic experts to discuss the new progress in the treatment of aortic diseases, and carried out cutting-edge technical training and difficult case discussions in the form of conference salons.
The reporter learned at the meeting that with the development of surgical technology and industrial materials, the current treatment of aortic diseases continues to develop in the direction of minimally invasive, rapid and efficient.
