The 3-year-old child's college playground was smashed, is it reasonable to sue the school after compensation?
2020-07-2605: 01: 11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed, and the child was compensated before suing the school.
□ our correspondent Zhao Yifan
When 3-year-old Xiaowen was playing on the playground of a certain university, he was accidentally hit in the head by Chen of the softball team while pitching.
After Chen paid compensation, Xiaowen's father, Mr. Wen, as Xiaowen's legal representative, sued the school to the court, demanding that the school where the playground was located apologize and pay a total of 20,000 yuan for medical expenses and moral damages.
Recently, after hearing the case, the Haidian District People's Court of Beijing held that the school had set up a protective net on the playground at the time of the incident, and had fulfilled its proper safety guarantee obligations, and Chen had paid compensation, based on which the judgment rejected the plaintiff's claim.
Mr. Wen claimed that during the summer vacation of 2019, he took Xiaowen to play on the school playground, when the softball team was training on the playground.
In order to avoid the risks posed by this, Xiaowen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents are active in the safe area designated by the softball team.
But then the softball team member Chen dropped his hand while pitching, causing the softball to fly over the guard net into the above-mentioned safe area and hit Xiaowen in the back of the head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believes that the facilities of the school stadium do not comply with relevant safety regulations, and the team and related facilities have not been effectively managed.
The school's negligence led to the above-mentioned incident, which caused Xiaowen to suffer great physical and mental pain, and also brought greater pain to his family. The school should bear legal responsibility for this.
In response, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net on the playground, and posted management regulations and training notices, informing them that entering the playground must maintain a safe distance from the training site and reminding them of their own safety. The plaintiff could not prove that the school "failed to meet its safety guarantee obligations" and therefore did not agree to compensation.
After the trial, the court held that the site of the incident was a site open to the public free of charge by the university involved. Although the school has a safety guarantee obligation for the management of the playground, this safety guarantee obligation only needs to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net on the playground, and it has fulfilled its proper safety guarantee obligations, and Chen also compensated Xiaowen for more than 2,000 yuan for various losses such as medical expenses and transportation costs in accordance with the previously reached compensation agreement. The two parties agreed to settle this dispute at one time.
Afterwards, Xiaowen's parents again claimed compensation from the school. There was no basis in the law, and the court ruled that all the plaintiff's claims were rejected.
After the verdict was pronounced, neither party appealed, and the judgment is now in effect.
According to Article 37 of my country's Tort Liability Law, schools, as managers of public places, have the obligation to ensure safety; in the case of damage caused by the actions of a third party, the third party bears tort liability, and the manager of a public place who fails to fulfill the obligation of safety guarantee should bear corresponding supplementary responsibilities.
The judge stated that as the administrator of a public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the entire place and foresee possible dangers and damages, so that he is most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or reduce the extent of damage, and the cost of avoiding and mitigating damage is the lowest, so the law stipulates that it shall bear the corresponding guarantee obligations for engaging in social activities.
In this case, for unspecified people entering the playground, which is open to the public free of charge, the school's safety guarantee obligations should be compatible with the social activities it engages in. Specifically, it should take basic safety measures and have an obligation to inform about hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive safety guarantee obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has set up a protective net and fulfilled its obligation to inform, it can be determined that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal liability.
In addition, for third-party infringement, even if the manager of a public place such as a school fails to fulfill his safety guarantee obligations, his liability is as a supplement to compensation for damages. According to the newly promulgated Civil Code, after the administrator assumes supplementary responsibilities, he can also recover from a third party.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victim should not expand the scope of the claim after he has received compensation from the direct infringer.
