At the Bayong Zhuokang sentry point, platoon commander Yu Wang and a soldier stood guard on duty.
In this place where the annual average temperature is more than ten degrees below zero, a row of simple barracks stands on the mountain pass. Not far from the barracks, a national flag is fluttering in the wind. The soldiers are on duty in the wind every day, and they need to regularly patrol higher-altitude locations.
The soldiers climbed the steep slope of the pile of rocks, requiring both hands and feet.
It was late July, when flowers and plants were flourishing in low-altitude areas, and in Bayong Zhuokang, only the ravine behind the barracks had relatively dense green.
Gao Peng, a soldier who has been stationed at the outpost for six years, pointed to the mountain ditch and said that this is their back garden. Only in July and August of each year can the grass grow slowly. After a while, it all turns yellow and is covered with snow.
Foot patrols can take about 9 hours.
Under the harsh plateau environment, the soldiers stationed here are accompanied by snow-capped mountains and glaciers all year round, and they also regularly patrol the higher mountain passes.
A few days ago, a patrol team composed of 8 fighters, led by instructor Liang Yixin, once again embarked on the patrol road.
Each soldier carries a weight of about 30 kilos and marches towards the target point early in the morning.
On the way, a soldier rebelled, and his comrades gave emergency help.
In addition to patrolling missions, the soldiers at the Bayong Zhuokang sentry point have to conduct tactical and physical training every day.
Time passed by, the altitude continued to rise, the oxygen content became lower and lower, and the physical strength continued to be overdrawn. These factors tested the will of the patrol members.
They clenched their teeth and insisted, stepping over several landslide points one after another, and crossing several emergency and dangerous beaches.
At about 16 o'clock, it was lunch time for the patrol members. They took out their own dry food and sat down on the spot at an altitude of more than 5,700 meters, accompanied by rain and snow, and supplemented their physical strength with food.
The soldiers at the Bayong Zhuokang sentry point conducted tactical and physical training.
During the break, they will play cards together, and the loser will do push-ups, both for entertainment and physical exercise.
After a short rest in the cold wind, they climbed to the target point of the patrol, took out the national flag on the mountain pass, and solemnly swore.
Behind them is the snow-capped mountains, and in front of them is a no-man's land for dozens of kilometers. They are the safest guardians of the country.
